			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Just a quick comment.  The fact that you have agreed to a EULA severely limits your legal options.  I am not familiar with the details of EQs EULA, but it probably limits legal action to the courts and laws of a specific state or to a specific arbitration orginization picked by Verant.<BR>
Be that as it may, no EULA, nor any fine print, is binding on any State or Federal gocernmental orginization that has jurisdiction over any claim that you may have, if that claim involves a violation of state or federal law or code.  For example, if the FTC believed that Verant had violated a law that it is responsible for enforcing, than the FTC can bring an enforcement action against Verant on your behalf.<BR>
I urge all those that are having problems to contact the FTC, your state's consumer affairs office and any other governmental orginization you can think of to investigate the business practices of Verant.  At the very least, the bad press from such an action would, hopefully, make Verant think more about its customers, and less about the bottom dollar.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
